      usage: "Proseuchomai is the most general NT word for prayer and appears 87 times. Matthew 6:5-9 uses it four times, and the Lord's Prayer itself is introduced with this word. It is distinguished from other prayer words by its relational orientation: deesis (supplication/petition, G1162) focuses on specific urgent need; eucharistia (thanksgiving, G2169) focuses on gratitude; but proseuchomai is the broad word for the ongoing conversation of the believer with God — prayer as a posture of life, not just as specific petitions.",
      connection: "1 Thessalonians 5:17 — 'Pray (proseuchomai) without ceasing.' The directional prefix in proseuchomai suggests that this command is not about maintaining an unbroken stream of verbal prayer but about living in an orientation toward God — a posture of continuous awareness of and communication with the Father. Prayer is less a scheduled activity and more a direction your life faces. The person who prays without ceasing is not always on their knees; they are always in their Father's presence.",
