    memoryVerse: "Even so, come, Lord Jesus. — Revelation 22:20",
    closingPrayer: "Lord Jesus — You are coming. Not as the Lamb but as the Lion. Not in humility but in glory. Not to be rejected but to be received. Not to suffer but to reign. All of history is moving toward that moment. Every seed of the gospel planted, every prayer prayed, every act of obedience, every life yielded — all of it is preparation for the morning when every eye shall see You and every knee shall bow. Thank You for a year of learning to know You better, to love what You love, and to walk more closely in the works You prepared for us. We are not finished — the works are still being walked in, the story is still being written, the witnesses are still being sent. But You are the ending. You are the destination. You are the hope that makes everything else bearable and everything eternal valuable. Even so, come, Lord Jesus. Amen.",

    leaderNote: "Week 52 is both the end of the curriculum and the beginning of a life. The session should feel like a commissioning, not a graduation party. The Jim Elliot story is deliberately placed at the very end: it brings together the themes of calling (W51), purity (W50), witnessing (W48), prayer (W47), and the armour of God (W45) — and shows them all lived out in one life, ending not in defeat but in fruitfulness. The final journal exercise — reviewing the year and writing a personal prayer ending with 'Even so, come, Lord Jesus' — should be given substantial time. If possible, end the session by reading those prayers aloud (those who are willing), and close the year with the group speaking Maranatha together. The four discussion questions move from grief to anticipation to reflection to commission — end on the last one. Each student should leave with one specific, concrete commitment for the coming year. This curriculum has always been preparing them for exactly this: the life they now go back to, equipped for the works God has prepared in advance for them to walk in.",
